 So he asks the question.

630
00:28:27,480 --> 00:28:30,940
 He says, "How can you tell when the night has gone

631
00:28:30,940 --> 00:28:33,220
 "and the morning has come?"

632
00:28:33,220 --> 00:28:34,060
 That's the question.

633
00:28:34,060 --> 00:28:36,820
 How can you tell when the night has gone

634
00:28:36,820 --> 00:28:38,620
 and the morning has come?

635
00:28:38,620 --> 00:28:41,200
 And so one of his students, the bright one,

636
00:28:41,200 --> 00:28:43,240
 is just right away, just raising his hand,

637
00:28:43,240 --> 00:28:45,340
 saying, "Oh, oh, oh, Rabbi, I know."

638
00:28:45,340 --> 00:28:48,860
 And he says, "Rabbi, is it when, at that time,

639
00:28:48,860 --> 00:28:50,460
 "right between night and day,

640
00:28:50,460 --> 00:28:54,300
 "is it at that time where you can look in the distance

641
00:28:54,300 --> 00:28:56,980
 "and tell the difference between a sheep and a goat?"

642
00:28:56,980 --> 00:28:59,980
 And it's a pretty good answer, right?

643
00:28:59,980 --> 00:29:02,380
 And then the rabbi says, "No."

644
00:29:02,380 --> 00:29:05,300
 And then the second one, the second brightest,

